This means all the unification is done at compile-time rather than runtime.

To make the type of the proof expressible with Qq, we have to construct the numeric literal up front.

I can't actually measure a meaningful performance difference in the tactic now,  but this spelling is more strongly-typed, and thus the semantics are clearer.

I tried building all of mathlib from scratch on my local machine.
```shell
$ git clean -xffd
$ time lake build
```

before (86decee4d83d85770dda012b1bc1c2329a02f773):

```
real	23m18.764s
user	411m43.242s
sys	18m21.281s
```
after (5e5c3f211f5f8eeb5585e1fe6240e3704101df4b):
```
real	23m14.771s
user	408m13.994s
sys	18m18.512s
```

So, this seems to confirm that this PR speeds things up a bit (but perhaps the difference is within measurement noise). I'm not sure what's going on with the bench bot.

Do we have a plausible explanation for why speedcenter is reporting a ~7% slowdown in total tactic execution time? The slowdown is consistent in the two speedcenter runs above, and it's well outside the usual range for that stat on other recent runs shown at http://speed.lean-fro.org/mathlib4/home.

The slowdown is consistent in the two speedcenter runs above, and it's well outside the usual range for that stat on other recent runs shown at http://speed.lean-fro.org/mathlib4/home.

No, I have no idea at all. Maybe @Kha has some ideas. It seems strange that our attempts at manual measurement suggest a performance improvement in spite of this statistic. It would of course be very helpful if we could track down whether this 97 seconds is spread across all files, or concentrated on just one.

There *are* some curious similar outliers at http://speed.lean-fro.org/mathlib4/repo-detail/e7b27246-a3e6-496a-b552-ff4b45c7236e?zoomYEnd=38562.133219999996&zoomXStart=1679636318772.1738&zoomXEnd=1693470372528.1082&dimensions=build%3Atactic%20execution%3A%3Asize%3Anative&dayEquidistant=true though I don't know if they are reproducible like this. Should "ntype" be "type"? Or is "ntype" a concept I need to learn about?

```suggestion
the return type accurately.
```
This was a ntypo

I suspect this could be made cleaner by pulling out this return type into its own `structure` declaration. Then you would not need to match on `_` so much, and maybe you could even add a constructor that takes `e'` implicitly.
I don't really see how the `_` matching would be avoided; I guess making it an explicit argument would make the `_` invisible, but morally it would still be there.

I was imagining something like

```lean
/-- Return value of the `mkProdPrf` function. -/
structure MkProdPrfResult {u : Level} {Œ± : Q(Type u)} (sŒ± : Q(Field $Œ±)) (v' e : Q($Œ±)) where
  {e' : Q($Œ±)}
  pf : Q($v' * $e = $e')
```

Then you could do
```lean
...
  | .node _ lhs rhs, ~q($e1 + $e2) => do
    let ‚ü®v1‚ü© ‚Üê mkProdPrf Œ± sŒ± v v' lhs e1
    let ‚ü®v2‚ü© ‚Üê mkProdPrf Œ± sŒ± v v' rhs e2
    return ‚ü®q(CancelDenoms.add_subst $v1 $v2)‚ü©
...
```

This seems more readable to me, but maybe I'm overthinking it.

I do agree that a `Result` structure like that is useful, I've used it as well for my own (experimental) tactic implementations. You could even reuse `Simp.Result` if you want to make it easy to adapt this into a `simproc`.

On the other hand, I consistent use of `Result` structures would require much more work than what this PR is intended to do. So I'll let Eric decide if this is worth it.
I adjusted to use a structure; though rather than removing the `_`s, I opted to make their values explicit to make it easier to follow what the tactic is doing.

@dwrensha, can you check you're happy with this?

bors d=@dwrensha
To satisfy the linter, you'll need to add doc comments for both fields.
